\begin_layout Standard
Fiscal policy has dynamic effects on households and other agents in the
 economy.
 To model these effects accurately, the model comprises a wide range of
 features that make it suitable for analysing fiscal policy.
 Specifically, it contains market incompleteness in the form of a zero borrowing
 constraint for households and a stochastic productivity process to match
 the high MPCs.
 Furthermore, it allows the analysis of transfer multipliers as Ricardian
 equivalence no longer holds.
 A two-asset structure allows to account for reasonable degrees of household
 wealth in the economy.
 On the supply side, nominal rigidities make output demand determined and
 sticky wages bound the volatility of profits
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(when wages are flexible, profits react in strongly countercyclical to output
 increases, which is not in line with the data)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and limit the earnings response to a fiscal stimulus (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "auclert2021mpcs,broer2021fiscal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ).
 Capital allows to account for the effects of crowding-out and for the powerful
 investment-consumption feedback highlighted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hagedornFiscalMultiplier2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Long-term government bonds reduce the dependence of the government budget
 on the real interest rate as it has to roll over debt less frequently.
 A gradual adjustment of the tax rate to debt-financed debt enables a deviation
 from a balanced budget rule.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In contrast to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, I leave out permanent heterogeneity and formulate the New Keynesian Philipps
 and wage Philipps curve without indexation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Households
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A continuum of households of unit mass populates the economy.
 Each household is subject to idiosyncratic risk through stochastic changes
 in its productivity level.
 The productivity levels 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 with states 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 behave according to a Markov process with a fixed transition matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

.
 In each period, the mass in state 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is given as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{s}$
\end_inset

 and aggregate productivity has mean one such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{s}\pi_{s}e(s)=1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Rouwenhorst method is used to transform the productivity process into
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{z}=7$
\end_inset

 discrete states.
 The household distribution is discretized into 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\ell}=n_{a}=100$
\end_inset

 states for the liquid and illiquid along asset distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell,a\in[0,30]$
\end_inset

.
 To account for the higher convexity of the consumption function at lower
 levels of wealth, the distance between states is made equidistant in logs.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Utility depends on consumption and hours worked through separable preferences
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(c)-v(n)$
\end_inset

.
 Households receive after-tax labour income 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{t}\equiv(1-\tau_{t})w_{t}N_{t}$
\end_inset

 that is then weighted by productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}\equiv Z_{t}e(s)$
\end_inset

 and government lump-sum transfers 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 They can invest in liquid assets 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 and illiquid assets 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 through a financial intermediary subject to a zero borrowing constraint.
 As in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Sticky_PE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 households are fully informed about their contemporaneous budget constraint
 and idiosyncratic productivity process.
 However, they only update their expectations about future aggregates with
 probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-\theta\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cut?
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

This results in the following dynamic programming problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V_{t}(l,a,a\__{k},s,k) & =\underset{c,l}{max\,\,}u(c)-v(N_{t})+\beta\mathbb{E}_{t-k}\left[\theta V_{t+1}(l',a',a\__{k},s',k+1)+(1-\theta)V_{t+1}(l',a',a',s',0)|s\right]\label{eq:V_full}\\
c+\ell' & =\left(1+r_{t}^{\ell}\right)\ell+Z_{t}e(s)+d\left(a\__{k},k\right)+T_{t}\nonumber \\
a' & =\left(1+r_{t}^{a}\right)a-d\left(a\__{k},k\right)\nonumber \\
\ell' & \geq0\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the value function in period t, and an apostrophe indicates the value
 of idiosyncratic states in the next period.
 A household that has not updated its expectations in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 observed the aggregate state 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 periods ago when it had illiquid assets 
\begin_inset Formula $a\__{k}$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(a\__{k},k\right)$
\end_inset

 governs the distribution from liquid to illiquid accounts
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
d_{t}\left(a\__{k},k\right) & =\frac{r^{a,ss}}{1+r^{a,ss}}a^{\epsilon}+\chi\left(a^{e}-\left(1+r^{a,ss}\right)\bar{a}\right)\label{eq:d_a}\\
a^{e} & =a_{t}^{e}\left(a\__{k},k\right)=\mathbb{E}_{t-k}\left[\left(1+r_{t}^{a}\right)a|a\__{k}\right]\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

This formulation of the illiquid asset choice simplifies the household problem
 as it leaves consumption or liquid assets as the only choice variable.
 At the same time, it ensures to a low MPC out of illiquid assets.
 The first term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:d_a"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 leads to a distribution to the liquid account when the return for illiquid
 assets or perceived return based on the last information update 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 period increases.
 Households only distribute a fraction of the increased value to the liquid
 account, ensuring a low MPC out of the illiquid assets.
 The second term, with a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 close to zero, leads to a slow transition back to the target value of illiquid
 assets 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}$
\end_inset

.
 In contrast to the predetermined liquid asset return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

, the illiquid asset return depends on the stock market's value in period
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 If this value rises unexpectedly in zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}^{a}$
\end_inset

 increases.
 Thus, households' illiquid assets increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and a fraction of this increase is redistributed to the liquid account.
 In the scenario where there is a transition back to the steady state in
 the following period, the illiquid asset stock is then slowly brought back
 to its steady state value through positive but low values of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The sticky information also lead to a delayed response to consume out of
 an increased illiquid asset stock
