\begin_layout Paragraph*
Households
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Households have constant CES utility over consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(c\right)=\frac{c^{1-\nu^{-1}}-1}{1-\nu^{-1}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the elasticity of intertemporal substitution (EIS).
 Disutility from labour is 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(n\right)=v_{0}n^{1+\varsigma^{-1}}/\left(1+\varsigma^{-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma$
\end_inset

 is the Frisch elasticity.
 Labour hours 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 are determined through aggregate labour demand 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 and are the same for all households.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

I calibrate aggregate household wealth to its average in the data of 
\begin_inset Formula $382\%$
\end_inset

 of GDP and to a ratio of liquid to illiquid assets of 9%, the preferred
 estimate from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kaplanMonetaryPolicyAccording2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

I omit permanent household heterogeneity compared to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, all households have the same discount factor and illiquid asset target
 corresponding to the average illiquid wealth in the economy.
 Thus, I don't match the illiquid asset distribution, and the illiquid assets
 target is significantly higher than the median wealth.
 However, due to the distribution rule out of illiquid assets and a parameter
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=0.009$
\end_inset

, the consumption response to an increase in the illiquid asset rate is
 muted.
 If the annual illiquid asset rate increases by 50 basis points for one
 year, annual consumption increases only by 0.44%.
 So even though the steady-state wealth in illiquid assets is high, changes
 in the illiquid asset return affect household consumption only marginally
 but over an extended time horizon
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chi_sensitivity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for an illustration of the adjustment in illiquid asset and consumption
 following a shock to the illiquid asset interest rate.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 calibrate their model to match the same MPC for each household group.
 As the aggregate redistribution to a marginal illiquid interest rate shock
 is the same, sois the initial consumption response.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Productivity follows a Markov process with a fixed probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{ss'}$
\end_inset

 of moving from state 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 to state 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

.
 This formulation represents a discrete approximation of a continuous income
 process that follows an AR(1) process 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}=\rho_{e}z_{t-1}+\epsilon_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 with persistence 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{e}$
\end_inset

 and innovations with standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 I follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mckayPowerForwardGuidance2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{e}=0.966$
\end_inset

 to match the quarterly persistence in earnings found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "flodenIdiosyncraticRiskUnited2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 I then use the discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and the standard deviation of earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 as free parameters to achieve goods market clearing and an annual MPC out
 of transfers of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.525$
\end_inset

 to match the MPCs out of lottery earnings found by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fagerengMPCHeterogeneityHousehold2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 match the MPC out of aggregate after-tax labour income, I use the MPC out
 of lump-sum transfers.
 This definition better fits the empirical MPCs out of lottery earnings
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fagerengMPCHeterogeneityHousehold2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which is the source of the MPC target.
 Shocks to labour income are weighted by productivity before entering a
 household's budget constraint, in contrast to the definition of lottery
 earnings, which are independent of productivity.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The second difference to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is that I use the standard deviation of earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{e}$
\end_inset

 as a free parameter, while they use the ratio of liquid assets to GDP.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This procedure yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0.9988$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{\epsilon}=0.36$
\end_inset

.
 The high value of the discount factor may seem remarkable, but the discount
 factor only affects the results through the consumption function, which
 targets specific characteristics.
 In the steady states, the consumption function aligns the MPC target and
 aggregate wealth through liquid wealth.
 As such, it does not play a role for the illiquid asset.
 Also, the negative value for the real rate of liquid assets requires a
 high discount factor.
 The standard deviation of earnings is slightly higher than the conventional
 parameters used in the literature
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mckayPowerForwardGuidance2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 use a lower standard deviation for innovation of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.13$
\end_inset

, also based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "flodenIdiosyncraticRiskUnited2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "guvenen2014nature"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find an annual standard deviation of around 0.6 which translates into a
 quarterly value of 0.16 assuming an AR(1) process with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{e}=0.966$
\end_inset

.
 Other papers, such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020,auclertIntertemporalKeynesianCross2018a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, use the estimates of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kaplanMonetaryPolicyAccording2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that yield a standard deviation for the annual log gross earnings of 0.92
 that translates to quarterly standard deviation of 0.25 given the annual
 persistence of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.91$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Var\left(e_{t}^{q}\right) & =\frac{Var\left(e_{t}^{a}\right)}{\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\left(\rho^{q}\right)^{2j}}\\
\rho^{q} & =\left(\rho^{a}\right)^{1/4}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This yields a higher wage inequality as the discretization based on the
 Rouwenhorst method results in more extreme productivity states at both
 ends of the distribution.
 However, this affects the consumption response to shocks only marginally,
 as the MPCs are still matched.
 For fiscal policy, this configuration leads to a slightly lower consumption
 response to changes in after-tax labour income.
 High productivity and low MPC households benefit more from an increase
 in labour income, leading to lower second-round effects as a higher share
 of this income increase goes into savings.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Regarding household inattention, I use the parameter from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0.935$
\end_inset

 as a baseline but illustrate the sensitivity to this parameter.
 Fiscal policy shocks are likely to receive a different degree of attention.
 Some fiscal adjustments, particularly transfers, are highly debated in
 the media leading to a potentially lower inattention level.
 Nevertheless, this does not imply that households can incorporate these
 adjustments into their expectations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Firms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the supply side, I calibrate hours worked to 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0}$
\end_inset

 and productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 to normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=1$
\end_inset

.
 The annual real interest rate in the steady state is 
\begin_inset Formula $r=5\%$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to the average real return on capital and government
 bonds from 1969–2019.
 The return on deposits minus inflation was negative at 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{\ell}=-1.5\%$
\end_inset

 over this time, yielding an intermediation spread of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=6.5\%$
\end_inset

 I calibrate the annual rate of capital depreciation to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}=5.3\%$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to the average ratio of depreciation to private fixed
 assets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p.19"
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 over 1969-2019.
 To match a capital-to-output ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $223\%$
\end_inset

 I set the capital share to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.24$
\end_inset

.
 The capitalized value of markups yields a steady-state markup of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{p}=\frac{\epsilon_{p}}{\epsilon_{p}-1}=\frac{1}{s^{ss}}=1.06$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The capitalized value of markups describe the discounted steam of markups
 that a firm earns over the life-cycle as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{p}=\sum_{t=1}\frac{D_{t}}{\left(1+r\right)^{t}}$
\end_inset

 which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{D^{ss}}{r^{ss}}$
\end_inset

 in the steady state.
 Without knowing the marginal costs 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

, the dividends can be derived from the financial intermediary flow of funds
 constraint as 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{ss}=A^{ss}-L^{ss}-q^{ss}B^{ss}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As usual in the literature, the wage markup is set to the price markup
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\epsilon_{p}}{\epsilon_{p}-1}=\frac{\epsilon_{w}}{\epsilon_{w}-1}$
\end_inset

.
 I set the investment adjustment cost parameter to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{K}=5.74$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "smetsShocksFrictionsUS207"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The investment adjustment cost parameter differs from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who have 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{K}=9$
\end_inset

.
 This value is outside of the spectrum usually found in the literature such
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{K}=2.48$
\end_inset

 in the model with and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{K}=1.58$
\end_inset

 without variable capital utilization from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "christiano2005nominal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "altigFirmspecificCapitalNominal2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also show that the estimate is higher if only monetary policy shocks are
 considered, which is why I choose to use the value from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "smetsShocksFrictionsUS207"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who consider a battery of shocks for their estimation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Unions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hagedornFiscalMultiplier2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in matching a Philipps curve parameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.03$
\end_inset

 for the NKPC and wage NKPC, respectively.
 This yields Calvo parameters of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\xi_{p}=\xi_{w}=0.86}}$
\end_inset

 which implies an average wage and price duration of 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 quarters
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Average duration of a price is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{1-\xi_{p}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, I set the discounting factor in the wage Philips curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{w}=\frac{1}{1+r^{ss}}$
\end_inset

 such that the degree of anticipation is in line with the literature.
 I refrain from using the estimates of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "auclertMicroJumpsMacro2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as this implies an average duration for prices and wages of 14 quarters,
 which is significantly higher than values conventionally used in the literature
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Many papers follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "christiano2005nominal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{w}=0.64$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{p}=0.6$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "smetsShocksFrictionsUS207"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{w}=0.70$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{p}=0.66$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The degree of rigidities plays an important role in the model.
 The degree of wage rigidities changes the speed of wage adjustment and
 thus the income path of households.
 The degree of price stickiness determines the path of real interest rates,
 which are important factors in the transmission of fiscal policy.
 The lower both Calvo parameters, the faster government consumption translates
 into higher wages and inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Government
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I set government spending 
\begin_inset Formula $G/Y$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $16\%$
\end_inset

, the average of US consumption expenditures divided by GDP from 1969 till
 2019.
 I set the value of government bonds to GDP to 
\begin_inset Formula $qB/Y=0.42$
